Aktualisieren von Styles und Assets

  • Zum Aktualisieren einfach die Datei unter dem identischen Namen hochladen.
  • Es wird automatisch die aktuelle Version der Datei verwendet. Eine Anpassung der CSS-Einstellungen für Experten ist nicht notwendig.

Einbindung von Schriftarten

Beim Hochladen von Schriftart-Dateien sollter der Upload-Button genutzt werden. Hierbei kann direkt der Dateityp auf "Schriftart" gesetzt werden. Im Anschluss muss über das Info-Symbol am Dateinamen die Detailseite zur Schriftart aufgerufen und dort die Attribute vervollständigt werden.

Nutzung der Assets im CSS

Alle Nicht-CSS Dateien die an diese Seite angehängt werden, sind als CSS-Variablen generisch verfügbar. Um diese im CSS zu nutzen, muss nur an der jeweiligen Stellen var(NAME) verwendet werden.

Overview

OKRs is short for Objectives (O) and Key Results (KR). It is a framework to prioritize and align a company on common goals and outcomes. Especially the last point needs emphasis: OKRs focus on outcome instead of output, it's about the generated impact of your actions instead of the concrete actions themselves.

OKRs can only be part of a holistic approach to company strategy and leadership. OKRs are a great tool for governing a couple of months at a time - typically 3 months, some use 4 months long cycles.

OKRs are only the bottom part of a hierarchy to guide the overall company:

  1. Vision
    The Vision is the governing North Star - it's most likely out of reach and it most often has a large social impact, the core answer to the question of "Why does the company exist at all?".
    The scope of the Vision is forever, it does not end.
  2. Mission
    The Mission describes the company's contribution to the Vision. It describes the What of the company.
    The Mission typically describes the next 5 to 10 years.
  3. Strategy
    The Strategy goes into details how the company will achieve its Mission. At best, a clear Strategy also contains 10 to 15 initiatives. An initiative is a precise and clear sentence that can be broken down into actionable chunks.
    The Strategy goes into the details of the next 1 to 2 years.
  4. Roadmap / Backlog
    The Roadmap / Backlog is the first element on the operative level. It breaks down the Strategy's initiatives and defines larger blocks that will be worked on in the future.
    The Roadmap / Backlog spans from 3 to 18 months.
  5. OKRs
    The OKRs define the lowest and most operative level. They explicitly set the focus and priorities for the next 3 months.

The time frame OKRs are defined for is called the OKR Cycle. As mentioned above, the OKR Cycle typically lasts either 3 months (i.e. a quarter) or 4 months. The OKR Cycle does not need to align to the calendar quarters or fiscal year of the company. It might be beneficial to shift the OKR Cycle so that year-end business in November or December do not match the end of a cycle and the last month of that cycle is January.

 

OKR Sets and the OKR Hierarchy

OKRs are defined in Sets. An OKR Set consists of up to 5 Objectives and up to 4 Key Results each, i.e. at most 20 items. These Sets form a hierarchy.

  • There is 1 Company Set for the CEO of the company defining the overall priorities and most important goals.
  • Every department has 1 Department Set with the department lead responsible for the Set.
  • For every team inside the department there can be additional sets, and so forth.

An OKR Set does not cover all the work the company / a department / a team does. It explicitly highlights the most important, most critical, and most inter-connected topics. To include an Objective into the corresponding OKR Set might be the consequence of the answers to the following questions.

  • What are the most important initiatives we want to finish in the next 3 months?
  • What are initiatives where we can make substantial progress, but maybe need larger contributions from other departments / teams / etc.?
  • Which criticial initiatives need to be advanced and we need to spotlight them?
  • What do we absolutely have to prepare or we cannot continue the 3 months after?
  • From our daily work, what are things we can significantly improve / change to be a lot better in the long run?

An important thing to consider is the last point - daily work. The OKR Set should give a realistic view on the work done by a department / team. However, it does not make sense to cover everything that the department / team is working on. The accounting team of course has to pay bills, process paychecks - but these actions are not part of the OKR Set. Pay attention to not just include strategic initiatives into the OKR Set and include improvements or advancements of typical activities often overlooked.

Alignment of OKR Sets and Importance

For the hierarchy it is important to ensure support. All OKR Sets form a hierarchy where a higher OKR Set is supported by lower Sets. Support is determined by mapping the Key Results (not Objectives) of lower Sets to the Key Results (not Objectives) of the higher Set. The work of a higher OKR Set (e.g. the Company Set) can only be accomplished by the contributions, i.e. the Key Results of the lower OKR Sets (the Department Sets). A lower OKR Set may always contain additional Objectives and Key Results that are not directly mappable to the higher OKR Set if the company aligns on doing so. Keep in mind: the higher OKR Set does not need to cover everything!

A note on importance: If an individual employee or team does not find its OKRs immediately in a higher OKR Set, this does not state anything of the importance of their work. Of course, the idea of OKRs is to define focus and priorities - but it definitely does not hold that additional work aside from the OKRs is "less important".

OKRs on different Levels

How far the OKRs get broken down or are implemented is up to the implementing company. From past experiences it does not make sense to implement OKRs only in an individual team or department. Without roling it out the the whole company (maybe just the upper level), other departments / teams still may focus on different priorities and thus be mis-aligned. Therefore, it is best to start with the company level (CEO / COO) and the department leads. After 1 or 2 successful OKR Cycles this can be pushed further down into the teams of the departments (all at once or one department after the other).

OKRs and Scrum

OKRs and Scrum go together really well. In a Scrum environment, the OKRs would be broken down to the Product Owner as the lowest level. The Product Owner would be the responsible for the OKR Set that applies to the whole Scrum team. For the other members of the team the OKRs essentially only influence the team's backlog from which the Sprints are populated.

OKRs for Individuals

It is theoretically possible for individual employees to have their own OKR Set (e.g. Google uses this approach). This requires a lot of discipline of all employees and the company in general with limited benefit. Using OKR Sets for individuals is to be handled with great care.

Unique Employee Assignments: Obvious but often violated is the concept of an individual employee being uniquely assigned to an OKR Set. This means that 1 employee in the end has exactly 1 parent OKR Set. There must be a unique order for deriving the OKRs in the company. Matrix organizations often violate this rule as both the supervisor as well as the business lead might have OKR Sets an individual should contribute to. It has to be absolutely clear which single OKR Set the employee contributes to.

About Objectives

As mentioned in the beginning, Objectives focus on the outcome. The main principle for an Objective is for it to describe a clearly fulfillable state. It is about having completed a specific thing latest by the end of the cycle. You have to be able to easily and clearly answer yes or no to the question: Did we complete the Objective?.

To get the key points of defining good Objectives and some commented examples check out the OKR Checklist 

About Key Results

The most important thing to remember for Key Results is to think about them as "bets" you are placing. The key is to identify the main drivers that when fulfilled most likely ensure the completion of the Objective.

Again, check out the OKR Checklist on how to define a good Key Result and some commented examples.

An important aspect to re-iterate from the checklist and to clarify is the correspondence of Key Results and KPIs in general. When defining KRs it is important to not just define some arbitrary improvements of KPIs but to be precise and place certain "bets", i.e. identify those things that in the end will have an impact on the KPIs. The mindset here is: whether you are doing the right things will become visible in the KPIs - but what you are trying to do is inside the KRs.

When defining KRs, another task is to identify cross-functional dependencies, i.e. which other department / team on the same level needs to provide input in order to implement the KR. The cross-functional dependencies can be categorized into two different types.

  1. Big Support
    A Big Support signals a significant contribution to be provided by the other department / team. It is so critical and maybe resource consuming that it requires a KR in the other department's / team's OKR Set.
  2. Small Support
    A Small Support clearly states the need for input from the other department / team, but is limited in the workload required. For example, if someone only needs to attend a couple of meetings or maybe spend 2 to 3 days of work, it suffices to mark it as Small Support.

The OKR Cycle

As mentioned above, the OKR Cycle typically lasts 3 months. The overall OKR Cycle looks like shown in the image below.

We will cover the Strategy Update, Pyramid, and OKR Workshop in the following.

Strategy Update

4 weeks before the current OKR Cycle ends, the Strategy Update takes place. In the Strategy Update the CEO again present the company's current strategy as well as highlights any changes that occurred since the last update. The company's strategy is one of the initial inputs to the Pyramid.

All employees are participants of the Strategy Update to make sure the whole company has a clear picture of the current strategy.

Pyramid (bottom-up)

During the Pyramid (the blue triangle in the image above), the OKR Sets of the teams and departments are created in a bottom-up approach. The individual team members know their daily work and pressing pain points best and also have their view on how the company's strategy can best be implemented. This process starts around 3 weeks before the switch.

Here, they derive the OKR Set that outlines the most important things from their point of view, taking into account everything they have learned in the past, including the strategy. Next, the team leads / departments gather all the information from the teams below them and compile their aggregated OKR Set to identify the major points on their level.

This continues until all departments have independently prepared their OKR Sets. At this point, the Company Set is not published yet.

At this stage it is also important for the OKR Set leads to coordinate with other departments / teams and communicate dependencies or requirements early. There should not be any suprises in the OKR Workshop regarding any OKRs someone else has never heard of.

OKR Workshop

In the middle of the Pyramid the 2 day OKR Workshop takes place, usually 1.5 to 2 weeks before the end of the OKR Cycle. The participants of the OKR Workshopconsist of the CEO/COO and all department leads, i.e. the leadership team. All of them have prepared their suggested OKR Sets.

OKR Workshop - Day 1

  1. Review and Retrospective
    At first, the past OKR Cycle and all its Objectives and Key Results are reviewed and a large retrospective takes place. The goal is to critically judge the progress the company made as well as derive lessons learned for future OKR Cycles.
  2. Set Presentation
    After the Review and Retrospective, the Company Set is presented to all participants before all Department Sets are presented by the department leads. At this point, participants ask questions if the presented OKRs need further explanation. There is no discussion on the Set content at this stage (whether these are the correct OKRs).
    When the KRs of a Department Set are presented, they are assigned to a KR of the Company Set, if possible. This allows to easily identify the support the Company Set has provided by the departments. Important: The assignement only takes place when there really is a direct match and real contribution.
  3. Identify Gaps and Candidates
    Having done the mapping in the previous step, it is now evident which KRs of the Company Set lack support. Moreover, departments can now nominate additional Objectives that should be lifted to company level.
  4. Define final Company Set
    The last part of Day 1 is the definition of the final Company Set. With all sets presented, new nominees, and identified lack of support, the leadership team will rework the Company Set and finalize it.

The most important outcome of Day 1 is the final Company Set.

OKR Workshop - Day 2

  1. Refresh Department Sets
    The updated and now finalized Company Set sometimes has an impact on the contributions of individual departments, especially if some KRs from the Company Set did lack support. This support must be added to and worked into the Department Sets. At this point it is also important to identify for every KR, what additional support is required (see [[#about-key-results]]).
  2. Finalize Deparment Sets
    The "last" step and closing part of the OKR Workshop is to finalize all individual Department Sets. The leadership team dives into every OKR Set, challenges formulation and content, and in the end agrees upon the indivual Objectives and Key Results. This process is very time and energy consuming, as the main goal is for everyone to have a clear understanding and reach a commonly agreed upon result.

Note: OKRs are not a democracy. In the end, it is a company decision (i.e. C-Level decision) on priorities and required outcomes. However, it should be clear for everyone why decisions were made as they are.

At the end of Day 2 and thus the end of the OKR Workshop we now have a fully finalized Company Set and for every department a Department Set.

Pyramid (top-down)

With the first 2 levels (company and departments) finalized, the Department Sets can now be broken down further. If implemented, the following teams' OKR Sets are now updated with the (potentially updated) Department Set.

During this phase, the Company Set as well as all the Department Sets are published and presented to the company.

Execution Phase

The simplest but most important phase of the overall OKR Cycle: execution. The agreed upon OKR Sets are now worked upon and continously updated. Following the goals and continously adhering to the meeting rhythm to surface problems and progress is key to success.

Note: The OKRs defined in the workshop for the corresponding quarter must be reviewed by the respective set lead/OKR owner with regard to the information security requirements before they are realized/planned (execution phase). This ensures that the information security requirements are fulfilled. If necessary, the information security officer must be informed or involved.

To ensure that the requirements are taken into account, the following must be noted:

  • In an early phase of the (external as well as internal) project, a risk assessment based on the defined procedure is carried out and renewed in case of changes to the project.
  • Measures are initiated for identified information security risks and implemented in the project.

Meeting Structure and Executing OKRs

During the Execution Phase a structure of regular meetings ensures an appropriate flow of information between all involved parties. All meetings follow the same agenda to ensure the right things are discussed. The information on individual KRs is continuously updated, too.

OKR Meetings

This section covers the meetings the OKR framework suggests. They should all be present in the company or else important information exchange is prohibited.

Who owns the Meeting

All OKR meetings can be separated into 2 categories: group meetings and 1-on-1s. For every category it is simple to define who owns the meeting:

  • Group Meetings
    A group meeting always consist of an OKR Set lead from a higher level and all the OKR Set leads from the level directly below that - example: the CEO and all department leads, or the department lead and all team leads (i.e. the Leadership Meeting).
    The lead of the higher OKR Set is the owner of the meeting.
    The focus of the discussion in group meetings are the higher OKR Set and problems that need cross-functional alignment or solutions.
  • 1-on-1s
    A 1-on-1 always consists of an OKR Set lead from a higher level and a single OKR Set lead from the level directly below that - example: the CEO and the Marketing lead, or the Product lead and a single Product Owner.
    The lead from the lower OKR Set is the owner of the meeting.
    The focus of the discussion in 1-on-1 meetings is the lower OKR Set.

Agenda

All meetings follow the same agenda that is outlined in Meetings. All meetings are prepared by the meeting owner in written form.

Just to repeat the most important aspect here: OKR Meetings are NOT a status update.

The OKR Meetings should not be an additional burden but should be looked at the other way round. These synchronizations meetings should already exist inside the company to ensure proper decision making methods and transparency of information. Talking about the OKRs as outlined in the agenda should just become "one more thing".

Calendar Structure

The key thing to the calendar structure is that the 1-on-1 meetings always take place before any group meetings. From the scope of the CEO the meeting structure would look like in the image below.

When OKRs are rolled out to more levels, the departments' 1-on-1s must also happen before the 1-on-1 of the department lead with the CEO. The team meeting for the department then takes place after the Leadership Meeting.

This might initially look like a lot of overhead - but it provides a very timely process for resolving problems. These get raised in 1-on-1s and can either be solved immediately bei the higher lead or the higher lead can take it further into his own 1-on-1. In the extreme case the issue is raised in the Leadership Meeting and is decided on there since all relevant stakeholders are present. Any information shared in the Leadership Meeting is then further shared in the team meetings. As a consequence, from raising the problem to having an updated information for everyone, is a matter of going through the meeting cycle.

Confidence and Grading

One of the core principles of OKRs is to focus on the outcome instead of the output. This directly impacts how the OKR process is governed and handled during the Execution Phase. During the OKR Cycle, the KRs are inspected every week by the OKR Set lead. But instead of tracking the progress that has already been completed, the confidence is tracked, also known as the KR's Confidence Level. If the Confidence Level goes down, we can focus on the affected KRs and either supply more resources or change our strategy.

Confidence Level: The Confidence Level determines the certainty (i.e. probability) with which the KR will be reached successfully by the end of the OKR Cycle (remember: successfully = at least 70%). Values range from 0.0 to 1.0 in typically 0.1 increments.

These are some general recommendations for choosing a specific Confidence Level:

  • 0.0: It is already certain you will not be able to successfully complete the KR. Nothing will help you, no more resources, no change of actions.
  • 0.1 / 0.2: There is only a slight chance of making the 70%. We really need to crack down on the KR to get to any higher chances of success.
  • 0.3: There is a high chance of failure already. We must put in more resources / devise an additional action plan to ensure that we get back on track.
  • 0.4: Progress is happening but slower than anticipated. Our actions did clearly miss the mark of their impact and we start thinking about alternatives / additional measures that could be employed.
  • 0.5: The KR has not yet been worked on or we still cannot predict in any way what our outcome might be.
  • 0.6: We are making progress but slowly, could be a little faster or our actions had impact but not yet to that extent as we expected them to have.
  • 0.7: We are on track, making good progress. There is quite some time with potential uncertainty left but we should be able to cover for things.
  • 0.8 / 0.9: We are perfectly on schedule, everything is working out as planned, there is not much left that could go wrong at all - if nothing unforeseeable happens we should hit the mark easily.
  • 1.0: The KR is already fulfilled to at least 70% and whatever will happen will not change the outcome.

At the end of the OKR Cycle, beginning when the bottom-up Pyramid starts, instead of updating the Confidence Level the OKR Set leads start filling in the KRs' Grades. Before the end of the OKR Cycle this is technically called the Grading Forecast. The values are finally updated at the last day of the OKR Cycle and from thereon archived.

Grade: The Grade is equal to the concrete value of the metric that is specified in the KR (e.g. the actual NPS score). Its value can be any number - for binary KRs it is either 1 if the KR is fulfilled or 0 otherwise.

Company Updates and the like

To keep everyone in the company updated, the updates especially on the Company Set are shared in All-Hands meetings. These should take place in regular intervals - maybe once a month. The updates of individual departments or teams can be discussed in department or team meetings but the OKR framework does not make an explicit suggestion there.

Lessons Learned

Focus on Drivers, Success is a By-Product

This holds true especially for revenue targets or customer satisfaction - success is most often measured as a KPI. The current annual recurring revenue (ARR) or net promoter score (NPS) are KPIs. When defining Objectives and Key Results, one tends to include concrete targets of those KPIs inside them. Always keep in mind that you need to ask: What exactly are you doing to get that ARR / improve the NPS?. The answers will be what you need to formulate as OKRs.

It's simple: do the right things (OKRs) and success will happen by itself (visible in KPIs).

This is a quick checklist for defining good OKRs.

Criteria for Objectives

These are the key criteria for a good Objective:

  • Defines a closed state in the future (can clearly be judged to either have been completed or not in the quarter).
  • Should focus on generating a concrete use / outcome.
  • Reachable with departments/teams own resources
  • No Evergreens - no goals that are always valid ("Increase Revenue", "Improve Performance")
  • Motiviational, inspiring goals, creating a clear imagination
  • Clear for everyone on the same level or below
  • Contributes to the overall strategy or the higher OKR set
  • Does not contain any metrics (especially no revenue numbers!)
  • No reference to any concrete business / project plan (e.g. "Complete Phase 1", "Reach Q3 Revenue")
  • At most 5 Objectives

Here are some examples of Objectives and some comments:

  • Be marketleader for XYZ.
    Aside from the Increase Revenue or Improve Performance examples above, this is an absolute Evergreen. It describes something you always aspire to be - and there is always someone who claims its them. Moreover, what is the concrete use of being the marketleader? Or ask yourself: what accomplishable next step are you going to do in order to become the marketleader in your opinion?
  • Make 14Mio EUR in revenue in Q3.
    Probably one of the most frequent mistakes is to put revenue targets and other metrics in the Objective. The Objective itself should not be measurable (with metrics). Again, focus on the outcome or initiative that you will complete in order to make the target happen, e.g. Launch populated App Store with payed apps to customers for self-service solutions..

Criteria for Key Results

These are the key criteria for a good Key Result:

  • Quantifiable with a clearly defined metric and expected value
  • A good result is defined at having completed at least 70%
  • Do not formulate KPIs but focus on the key contributors / drivers - think: "What are the bets I'm placing and going to do that will make reaching the Objective more likely?"
  • Focus on the most promising drivers (their results push the Objective most)
  • Key Results are independent from each other (if one KR does not work out you still have the others to rely on)
  • No milestones, no checklists!
  • Divides the Objective as good as possible according to MECE (Mutually Exclusive, Collectively Exhaustive)
  • At most 4 Key Results

Here are some examples of Key Results and some comments:

  • Publish feature XYZ.
    This is a binary KR. It does not have a metric which could be fulfilled to a certain degree - it is either published, or not. In special cases you might have to put those in to express something explicitly. However, you should always focus on what you are trying to achieve. Developing and publishing a feature most often does not provide any benefit by itself - has it been released to users, did they use it at all, did it really speed up their workflow? Focus on the impact the feature will have and the problem you are trying to solve.
  • Write 5 new blog posts.
    This KR has a nice and clearly defined metric to measure. However, it only describes the quantity and neglects the quality of the driver. You will most likely not contribute to the Objective, if nobody reads the blog posts. In these situations ensure an additional quality metric, e.g. Wirte 3 new blog posts with at least 1.000 unique visitors - include a metric that quantifies if it really helped. By that you can generate learnings afterwards, like did we use the wrong content or maybe failed in SEO?
  • Increase customer satisfaction by 10%.
    Again a clearly defined metric inside the KR. Once more, it does not describe a bet you are making but merely describes the KPI you would use to see if something you did was successful - but what is the something you will try doing? This can be tricky to solve as you do not want to describe conrete actions but neither do you want to stay too abstract and only mention the general KPI.

page.name: OKR Meeting Agenda
page.content:
First and foremost: an OKR Meeting is NOT a status update.

The OKR Meeting Agenda simply contains the OKRS structure.

  1. OKRs
  2. KPIs
  3. Resources
  4. Structure

OKRs

Of course, either the higher or lower OKR Set are one essential part of the meeting. There are a few aspects that are covered for every Objective and Key Result if applicable.

  1. Results
    Has there been a substantial result or breakthrough, any successes that can be celebrated together? If there is just business as usual there is no need to report this (remember: no status meeting).
  2. Problems
    One of the key things to successfully implement OKRs is focusing on Blockers. What is preventing the work from getting done, what is endangering the successful completion of the Objective or Key Result? Are there any decision that need to be made (hopefully directly in a 1-on-1) or need to be taken elsewhere? The Blockers are essentially the same as Impediments in Scrum.
  3. Learnings
    OKRs is an agile methodology and thus puts great emphasis on generating Learnings. Report what you changed in order to overcome issues, what other departments / teams should adopt. Go into details that did not work well and the knowledge generated from those.
  4. Next Steps
    What is going to happen until the next meeting? Are there concrete actions to be taken, what will be changed / clarified / decided on until next time?

KPIs

In the OKRs themselves we focus on the outcome and not the output of things. Nevertheless, we need to track the progress and current state of affairs, for example with respect to currently active users or monthly recurring revenue. The KPIs that are relevant for the discussed OKR Set and meeting scope are part of this agenda item.

KPIs should especially surface if the bets we placed in our OKR Sets seem to turn out unsuccessful. By cross-checking we can pro-actively monitor and derive measures if required.

The cplace way We do not track KPIs in all areas or for all needs - don't be too anxious to have to talk about KPIs. But let's get better at having a numerical understanding of our business 

Resources

This agenda item suits to clarify resource requirements. These can range from internal shifting between teams, to talking about new head count and raising recruiting needs to HR. Questions regarding the available budget or spending should also be discussed here.

Structure

The last part covers the process-side of things. Suggestions for improving the overall process or how the organization handles OKRs and other issues in general can be discussed here.

Set Lead

The Set Lead is responsible to succesfully carry out the whole set including objectives and key results. The lead is responsible for the cross company communication and administrational parts of the OKR method. It includes setting up the meetings, like the 1 on 1's, leadership meetings and OKR workshop.

Besides the own responsibilities of the assigned set, the lead needs to ensure the support of the organizational unit to other departments where required. It also includes adding one objective to reach the goal of another department.

Set Contributor

The set contributors are the employees participating in reaching the objectives of this set. It includes every involved people of the corresponding department that actively works on one of the key results.

A set contributor's responsiblities are updating the progress, work on the assigned key results and tasks, take part in the meetings and add possible topics in the workshop for future objectives or key results.

Set Lead

The Set Lead is responsible to succesfully carry out the whole set including objectives and key results. The lead is responsible for the cross company communication and administrational parts of the OKR method. It includes setting up the meetings, like the 1 on 1's, leadership meetings and OKR workshop.

Besides the own responsibilities of the assigned set, the lead needs to ensure the support of the organizational unit to other departments where required. It also includes adding one objective to reach the goal of another department.

Set Contributor

The set contributors are the employees participating in reaching the objectives of this set. It includes every involved people of the corresponding department that actively works on one of the key results.

A set contributor's responsiblities are updating the progress, work on the assigned key results and tasks, take part in the meetings and add possible topics in the workshop for future objectives or key results.

shortHelp.en: If the attribute value of an event is equal to the event class' attribute value, the event is assigned to this event class. If the attribute is a reference, the value of "attributeValue" represents the (internal) name of the referred page. Only the first event class fulfilling this condition will be applied.
shortHelp.de: Gleicht das in der Ereignisklasse angegebene Attribut dem angegeben Wert, so wird eine Ereignisseite dieser Ereignisklasse zugeordnet. Ist das Attribut eine Referenz, so repräsentiert der angegebene Attributwert den (internen) Namen der referenzierten Seite. Trifft keine definierte Ereignisklasse zu, oder sind keine zusätzlichen Ereignisklassen definiert, wird der Ereignistyp selbst als Ereignisklasse zugeordnet.

shortHelp.en: The display name of the event class which, e.g., is used for the event class selection within the calendar widget.
shortHelp.de: Der Anzeigename der Ereignisklasse, welcher z.B. bei der Ereignisklassenauswahl des Kalendars verwendet wird.

shortHelp.en: The color of the event class. This attribute is optional. If it is not defined, the color of the event type will be applied.
shortHelp.de: Farbe der Ereignisklasse. Dieses Attribut ist optional. Wird es nicht angegeben, wird die Farbe des Ereignistyps als Farbe der Ereignisklasse verwendet.

shortHelp.en: The order of the event types which, e.g., is used for the menu within the calendar widget to create new events.
shortHelp.de: Die Reihenfolge der Ereignistypen, wie sie beispielsweise im Menü zur Erzeugung neuer Ereignisse im Kalendar angezeigt werden.

shortHelp.en: The cplace type which has to be registered as event type. In order to specifiy the start and end date attributes as well as event classes, you have to save the event type after its value was changed.
shortHelp.de: Der cplace-Typ, welcher als Ereignistyp registriert werden soll. Um das Start- und Enddatumsattribut als auch Ereignisklassenzu definieren, müssen Sie nach dessen Aktualisierung den Ereignistyp erst speichern

shortHelp.en: The attribute of the selected cplace type which holds the start date of the event.
shortHelp.de: Das Attribut des gewählten cPlace-Typs, welches das Startdatum des Ereignisses enthält.

shortHelp.en: The attribute of the selected cplace type which holds the end date of the event.
shortHelp.de: Das Attribut des gewählten cPlace-Typs, welches das Enddatum des Ereignisses enthält.

shortHelp.en: The color of the event type. This color will be applied if either no event class is specified for this type, or if none of the defined event classes is applicable.
shortHelp.de: Standardfarbe des Ereignistyps. Diese Farbe wird angewandt, wenn entweder keine Ereignisklassen in der Konfiguration des Typs definiert ist, oder wenn für eine bestimmte Ereignisseite keine Ereignisklasse angewandet werden kann.

shortHelp.en: This pattern is used to generate the names of the events in the calendar. The possible attributes of the pattern will be derived from the event type. Is no pattern defined, the event name will be the name of the underlying page of the event. To use this name as part of the pattern, use $name$ as placeholder.
shortHelp.de: Das hier angegegebene Muster wird verwendet um die Namen der Ereignisse im Kalender zu erzeugen. Die möglichen Attribute des Musters leiten sich vom Ereignistyp ab. Ist kein Muster angegeben, wird der Name der dem Ereignis zugrunde liegenden Seite verwendet. Möchte man diesen Namen ebenfalls im Muster verwenden, kann $name$ als Platzhalter verwendet werden.

shortHelp.en: Event classes which distinguish the events of the respective type into specific event classes based on the values of attributes. They will be tested for applicability in the defined order. If one event class is applicable, the conditions of the subsequent ones won't be tested. If none of the event classes is applicable, the event type itself will be implicitly interpreted as event class.
shortHelp.de: Jeder Ereignistyp kann eine beliebige Menge von Ereignisklassen definieren, welche den entsprechenden Ereignistyp noch weiter anhand bestimmter Attributwerte unterteilen können. Die Ereignisklassen werden dabei in der definierten Reihenfolge auf deren Anwendbarkeit getestet.
